Passwords and account aging.

Two commands manage passwords and how they age over time. The first is passwd. Run on its own, it changes your own password interactively. Given a username, and with sudo, it changes that user's password. It also does more than set passwords: with dash l it locks an account, with dash u it unlocks one, with dash e it expires the password so the user is forced to change it at their next login, and with dash d it deletes the password entirely, which leaves the account requiring no password at all and is dangerous.

The second command is ch-age, which controls password aging: how often a user must change their password, how soon they are warned, and when the account expires. With dash l it lists a user's current aging settings. Dash capital-m sets the maximum password age in days, after which a change is forced. Dash m, lowercase, sets the minimum age, the shortest time before it may be changed again. Dash capital-w sets how many days ahead of expiry to start warning the user. Dash capital-e sets a date on which the whole account expires, and giving it minus one removes that expiry. And setting the last-change date to zero forces a password change at the next login.

For the exam, be comfortable with the lock, unlock, and expire options of passwd, and with the list, maximum-age, warn, and expiry options of ch-age. On real production systems, password policy usually combines these aging defaults with quality rules enforced through the authentication framework, which we preview a little later.
